of light has a distinct wavelength. All of this is testable in a high 
school science class. 
In an oxygen/nitrogen atmosphere the molecules are just the right size to 
scatter blue wavelength light that is coming down more or less directly 
above us. 
However at sunrise and sunset, the light is coming at an angle, and 
traveling through much more atmosphere to reach us. This means that all the 
dust particles and larger molecules have a chance to scatter the longer 
wavelength reds and oranges. And because it's not overhead (where the 
strength of the sunlight is at it's peak) the blue scattering gives way to 
the reds, creating gorgeous scenes that go from blistering red, thru bands 
of yellow and green and darkening blues on the opposite side (behind you).

Cities with the worst pollution have the most amazing sunsets. 

The amount of heat that hits us is similar to equatorial vs arctic 
temperatures. When sunlight hits head on at the equator it is concentrated 
onto a smaller area. Whereas the light hitting the poles is spread across 
an arc, leaving them cooler year round.

at an angle in the morning/night and more direct at noon.

+Jonathan Perez "You want a wormhole? Imagine it in your head Boom! Done! 
Wormhole created!"

I'm afraid you have summarized my skepticism about what some scientists 
have been coming up with over the last generation or two. Of course, we're 
supposed to trust them because they can create big, complex equations, far 
beyond the ability of much more than a handful of people to evaluate. But I 
have a feeling that they no more support some of these modern "hypotheses" 
than (a + b^n) / n = x is proof of God, even though that story is a legend.

As cosmology pushes closer to the limits of what can actually be observed 
or known, speculations proliferate in the absence of evidence. This gets 
certain scientists book deals, TV appearances, lecture tours, and most 
importantly, funding. (I love science, so the more funding they can get, 
the better.) These people become media darlings, but I fear much of what we 
have heard will turn out to be bunk. Or these ideas may persist because 
they can never be proven *or* disproven. Wormholes, M-Theory, string 
theory, white holes, dark matter, dark energy, multiverses, 11-dimensional 
Universe, and several others just seem to peg my bullshit meter. I hope I'm 
wrong, but on most of these, I may not be.

There is a very powerful bias that we "have only scratched the surface" 
where cosmology and theoretical physics are concerned. And the tendency to 
be perhaps too open-minded about these new ideas may be based on a fear of 
looking like those in the past who incorrectly claimed such-and-so to be 
impossible or nonsense. That fear might be unjustified, though. Perhaps 
there *is* a limit on what can be known, by anybody, anywhere, any time, 
about the nature of the Universe, and possibly we are fast approaching it. 
Just like there is no likelihood of discovering any new continents on 
earth, there may be little left to learn about the physical properties and 
major constituents of the Universe. That thought scares the hell out of 
theoretical physicists and cosmologists. Understandably.

parallel distance compared with its perpendicular distance, but it would 
still be round. That is to say that the furthest edges of the earth would
